(510,'Individual','Kalimaye Road, Nouvelle France','','Nouvelle France','Grand Port','51302','Mauritius','Mr.','Rushil Tanveer','Ramdharee','Rushilrt','ramdharee.rushil@gmail.com','+230-928-3506','2017-08-28 15:00:07',1,1,'I consider myself to be fortunate to have had the opportunity to take part in two Model United Nations conferences in my country as a delegate and being proclaimed best delegate together with forming part of best delegations. The two Model United conferences were the Zonal Model United Nations conference and the National Model United Nations conference of my country, Mauritius. \r\nHaving little experience in public speaking at the time of selections for the Model United Nations conference at my college in February, I was hesitant to the proposals made by my former tutors to participate in the conference. The selection judged us on our orating and analytical skills and we had to criticize as well as provide concrete solutions to given topics. It turned out that I came first out of the lot for the selection stage as according to the jury panel and I had been the most fluent and better that my friends at explaining concepts. From that particular moment, I understood that this was what I loved doing and what I wanted to do, debating. \r\nSome weeks later, our 2 delegations had been assigned the countries that they were to represent respectively and I formed part in the delegation representing Sweden, the other one being Ivory Coast. Other than being acquainted to the other delegates in my delegation, there was not much synergy between us and we were behaving as complete strangers. After numerous training sessions presided by our mentors, (the former Model United Nations delegates of the previous year) the preparation for the Zonal Model United Nations conference taught me the value of friendship and forging bonds- they are invaluable. We started this journey together, worked hard day and had many sleepless nights to prepare ourselves for conference day and our mentors acknowledged us and were proud of all that what we had done- we came a long way since together.\r\nThe Zonal Model United Nations conference felt like a culminating point for me. The conference lasted 2 days and was the only time where I felt where we could show our worth and all our work. I had to read our country statement in the General assembly on day 1 and this was an all-new experience - to speak in front of more than five hundred persons who were all well dressed and attentively listening to every word I was saying. Every word I said in the microphone felt like it had weight and I had to be precise in my intonation for an even better delivery. What lasted for 90 seconds in the General Assembly, felt like forever, personally and I felt relieved after the country statement delivery had ended. I also felt that I had overcome my fears and the stage freight that I faced. \r\nWhen stepping into the Science and Technology commission room, I felt what was like an adrenaline rush. It was a desire to debate, to prove and defend our resolution and find flaws in other’s debate and solutions proposed- in the common goal of having plausible and feasible measures to address the world’s most pressing issues. I listened to every single delegate who came forward to debate and every time I had at least one question to ask on some point mentioned that was not specific. I conveyed both of my debates out loud and as clear as I could to captivate as much attention and to be easy to understand. Stepping out of the commission room on day two I had the conviction that I did my best out there and again it was a feeling of relief that I could go though both days together with my fellow delegates and all went well.\r\nThe proclamation was done with best delegates first and then best delegations. I was proclaimed best delegate of the Science and Technology commission but I had mixed feelings- I felt a sense of accomplishment that my hard work paid off but at the same time I felt that this award will not be worthy of being won if both our delegations were proclaimed best delegations. Then my delegation was announced best delegation and we went on stage, but still the delegation of Ivory Coast was missing. During that tense moment, all Sweden delegates were holding hands hoping that all of us together WE WIN. I really cherish that moment and it was a very emotional moment for all of us, barely saying a word to each other but understanding everyone. We had developed such a deep connection among ourselves; we could express and tell what the other was feeling and thinking with facial expressions and body language only and words.\r\nMoving on to the National Model United Nations conference, it was again the same feeling that only that special conference can give. This time around I was assigned to be a delegate representing Saudi Arabia in the Political commission, the other delegation from my school representing Angola.  Even more persons to talk in front of and the conference becomes more challenging. National Model United Nations conference had the best students in the country. Together we worked even harder and this time, my co-delegates put me as the head of delegation to coordinate our work even more efficiently. That greatly improved my leadership and management skills. \r\nPolitical commission for the National Model United Nations, had no equal flooring to the point where, only a few delegates could express themselves fully. I was given the floor for two debates and had only 1 point of information allowed compared to the other delegates who got 3 points of information minimum. Moreover, the chairpersons were biased towards some delegates and rejected point of orders when they were right, few rights of reply were entertained even though many false accusations were made, only to mention a few!  A heavy atmosphere, of frustration, could be felt in the commission room. At the time of proclamation, neither Saudi Arabia nor Angola were proclaimed best delegates and we left the General Assembly with heavy hearts. We discussed what happened in each of our respective commission rooms and cheered up each other together with that misery laugh. Proclamation was over, the National Model United Nations conference was over and we accepted all of it and I feel like this is the best scenario that could have happened. One of the chairpersons said,” you do not have to be proclaimed winners to be winners.” At first, I thought those were words were blunt and were meant to console some sorrowful minds, but reflecting upon those words taught me that life was not only about winning. \r\n I can say that I have had the complete package of the Model United Nations conference with the good and the bad. At the end of the day though, I forged strong bonds with my friends (whom I shall call brothers), I learned so many things about the United Nations and its role in dealing with all the scourges that our world faces today, improved my orating skills,  I was taught to accept things and that they do not always happen as expected no matter how much effort is done, I learned how cruel our world really is out there and most importantly that winning does not mean everything- you are the real winner only when everyone acknowledges that you are the best, and it is only when you work hard and give your best that you are happy.\r\nI am thankful to every single person stood with me in the beginning of this journey. Participating in the Model United Nations conference has made be grown much. Every experience I got was enriching in one way or the other and I firmly believe that the Model United Nations conferences will forge our future leaders.','United Kingdom','Russia','Japan','France','China','SaudiArabia',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
